According to the summary of the new fitted model, we could see that points=11.6372+3.5255attitude. The multiple R squared measures how much of the variability in the dependent variable (points) is caused by the variability in the independent variables (attitude, stra and surf). In model 1 it is 21% and in model 2 it is 19.1%. This demonstrates that attitude is not a strong factor for obtaining good marks. In the first model, there is a prediction that all other things held constant as points increase by 1 score, attitude and stra increase by 3.4 and 0.9 respectively but surf reduces by 0.6. In the second model, there is a prediction that as points increase by 1 score, attitude will increase by 3.5, holding other factors constant.

Q3: Chosen Vars and hypothesis

The four interesting variables I have chosen are age (age), extra educational support (schoolsup), free time after school (freetime) and weekly study time (studytime). I draw the following hypothesis; expect a positive coefficient between alcohol consumption and age as legal age for drinking alcohol is high; expect negative coefficient between alcohol consumption and extra education support as less time is spent for leisure (drinking); expect positive coefficient between alcohol consumption and free time after school as more time is spend on leisure (drinking) and lastly expect a negative coefficient between alcohol consumption and study time as less time is spent on leisure (drinking) is more time is committed to studying.

Q4: Visualization and relationships

#Bar plots
g1 <- ggplot(data = pormath, aes(x = age , fill = high_use))
g1 + geom_bar()+ facet_wrap("high_use")+ ggtitle("Student age by alcohol consumption")

g2 <- ggplot(data = pormath, aes(x = schoolsup , fill = high_use))
g2 + geom_bar()+ facet_wrap("high_use")+ ggtitle("Student Extra support by alcohol consumption")

g3 <- ggplot(data = pormath, aes(x = freetime , fill = high_use))
g3 + geom_bar()+ facet_wrap("high_use")+ ggtitle("Student free time by alcohol consumption")

g4 <- ggplot(data = pormath, aes(x = studytime , fill = high_use))
g4 + geom_bar()+ facet_wrap("high_use")+ ggtitle("Student study time by alcohol consumption")

#Box plots
g1 <- ggplot(pormath, aes(x = high_use, y = age ))
g1 + geom_boxplot() + ylab("age")+ ggtitle("Student age by alcohol consumption")

g3 <- ggplot(pormath, aes(x = high_use, y = freetime ))
g3 + geom_boxplot() + ylab("Free time")+ ggtitle("Student Free time by alcohol consumption")

g4 <- ggplot(pormath, aes(x = high_use, y = studytime ))
g4 + geom_boxplot() + ylab("Study time")+ ggtitle("Student study time by alcohol consumption")

Bar plots are used to graphically explore the distributions of your chosen variables and their relationships with alcohol consumption (high_use). It is generally seen from the variables chosen that students in the sample are not very heavy alcohol consumers. For age we see more students in the FALSE category as they get older. Although some heavy alcohol consumption is recorded in the TRUE category it does not match up to the alternate category. We however confirm the initial hypothesis with the box plot which shows a huge mass as age increases. For extra school support it is seen that in the TRUE category this is a significant increase when there is no extra support; confirming the initial hypothesis. For free time we see that in the TRUE category, there is a rise in alcohol consumption when free time increases. This confirms the hypothesis. For study time it is seen that alcohol consumption decreases as study time increases as seen in the TRUE category. It is also observed that there is more mass in the FALSE category pointing to the fact that more students spend more time on studying. The initial hypothesis is also confirmed by the box plot.

According to the summary of the fitted model, we could see that from the coefficients high_use=-4.1682+0.2057age-0.1006schoolsup+0.32431freetime+-0.5920studytime. All signs for each coefficient confirms the initial hypothesis. All coefficients are statitiscally significant with the exception of ectra support (schoolsup). Based on the odd ratio, high_use=0.0155+1.228age+0.9046schoolsup+1.3831freetime+0.553studytime. For age, freetime and studytime we interpret each variable as a change in the odds ratio when high_use changes by one unit when all other things are held constant. However, with a factor variable line schoolsup, we interpret this in reference to the other category, thus, with reference to students without extra support, the odds ratio of alcohol consumption will decrease by 0.9 for those students who have extra support.

Q6: Model Predictions

# predict() the probability of high_use
probabilities <- predict(m, type = "response")

# add the predicted probabilities to 'alc'
pormath <- mutate(pormath, probability = probabilities)

# use the probabilities to make a prediction of high_use
pormath <- mutate(pormath, prediction = probability > 0.5)

# see the last ten original classes, predicted probabilities, and class predictions
select(pormath, age, freetime, studytime, high_use, probability, prediction) %>% tail(10)

# define a loss function (mean prediction error)
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}
# call loss_func to compute the average number of wrong predictions in the (training) data
loss_func(class = pormath$high_use, prob = pormath$probability)
## [1] 0.2972973

The model performs well as it predicts only 0.30 observations incorrectly.

# the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "orange", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

# target classes as numeric
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

# plot the lda results
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1)

# save the correct classes from test data
correct_classes <- test$crime

lda.pred <- predict(lda.fit, newdata = test)

# cross tabulate the results
table(correct = correct_classes, predicted = lda.pred$class)
##           predicted
## correct    low med_low med_high high
##   low       18      10        0    0
##   med_low    6      14        1    0
##   med_high   1      10       14    1
##   high       0       0        1   26

The LDA model does quite well at predicting the correct model. Ideally, we would prefer that all the cases to lie on the diagonal of the cross tab matrix. We see a greater mass of the data lying on the diagonal. The highest misallocation is for 12 cases where the model predicts them as med_high but the data (observed) classifies them as med_low. The lowest misallocation is for 1 case where the model predicts as high but the data (observed) classifies this as med_high.

As we increase the number of clusters we approach the optimal cluster number. In the elbow method we see how increasing the number of the clusters contribute separating the clusters in a meaningful way, not in a marginal way. The bend indicates that additional clusters beyond the third (3) have little value. Due to poor convergence the Gap Statistic Method gives an optimal of 26. However, we choose the optimal 3 as predicted by the elbow method as this is more realistic.Bear in mind that these clusterd are groups and it is easy to visualize three groups as compared to 26.

biplot(pca_human1, choices = 1:2, cex = c(0.8, 1), col = c("grey40", "deeppink2"))

The two biplots are very different which is mainly due to the fact that the data is normalized with mean 0 and variance constant. It is important to note that the graphs display the multiple correlations between the original features of the variables and the principal components as displayed in a lower 2 dimensional representation. The arrows show the connections between the original variables and the Principal components. When the data is not standardized, we can see the obvious negative relationship only between Maternal Mortality Ratio and Gross National Income per Capita. However, when data is standardized we can tell the relationships between all the variables in the dataset which conforms to theory. For instance, it is natural to see positive relations between Adolescent Birth Rate and Maternal Mortality Ratio as well as between Female Population with Secondary Education and Expected Years of Education. This is seen also from the biplots. For negative relationships, as we would see in the real world, the standardized data also shows inverse relations between Gross National Income per Capita and Adolescent Birth Rate/Maternal Mortality Ratio as well as Expected Years of Education and Adolescent Birth Rate/Maternal Mortality Ratio.

Q4: Interpretations of first two PC dimensions

The extent or direction to which the features (variables) point in the biplot tells which principal component contributes most to this magnitude. When the data is standardized, we observe that Percentage Representation in Parliament and Female labour force participation are mainly influenced by the first principal component (PC1) whiles the rest of the variables are mainly influenced by the second principal component (PC2)

Finally, we perform a two-sample t-test and observe the differences as seen in the boxplots above. We compute the analysis of variance table for the fitted model. We see that the baseline RATS is strongly related to the Rats values taken after treatment (Group) has begun, but there is still no evidence of a treatment (Group) difference even after conditioning on the baseline value.

# Perform a two-sample t-test

# Let us put groups 2 and 3 together in order to run the t-test
RATSL8S1$Group[which(RATSL8S1$Group==2)] <- 3
t.test(mean~Group, data = RATSL8S1, var.equal = TRUE)

Analysis of Longitudinal Data Part 2

In this part we go a little deeper to the analysis comparing to the Part 1. As in the course book it says:

The summary measure approach to the analysis of longitudinal data described in the previous chapter sometimes provides a useful first step in making inferences about the data, but it is really only ever a first step, and a more complete and a more appropriate analysis will involve fitting a suitable model to the data and estimating parameters that link the explanatory variables of interest to the repeated measures of the response variable

To that end, we use Linear Mixed Effects Models for repeated measures data. To begin to see how linear mixed effects models are applied in practice, we shall use some data from Davis (2002): Here 40 male subjects were randomly assigned to one of two treatment groups and each subject was rated on the brief psychiatric rating scale (BPRS) measured before treatment began (week 0) and then at weekly intervals for eight weeks. The BPRS assesses the level of 18 symptom constructs such as hostility, suspiciousness, hallucinations and grandiosity; each of these is rated from one (not present) to seven (extremely severe). The scale is used to evaluate patients suspected of having schizophrenia.

We now describe the data in the similar way as for RATS data. The summaries and structure and a plot for the treatment group and control group is given. We observe the following

the BPRS score of almost all the men is decreasing over the eight weeks of the study. -the men who have higher BPRS values at the beginning tend to have higher values throughout the study. there are substantial individual differences and variability appears to decrease with time.

This model assumes independence of the repeated measures of brps, which is unrealistic. Next we consider the random intercept model. Fitting a random intercept model allows the linear regression fit for each subject to differ in intercept from other subjects.

Next we create a random intercept and random slope model. Fitting a random intercept and random slope model allows the linear regression fits for each individual to differ in intercept but also in slope. This way it is possible to account for the individual differences in the rats growth profiles, but also the effect of time.

# create a random intercept and random slope model
BPRSL_ref1 <- lmer(bprs ~ week + treatment + (week | subject), data = BPRSL, REML = FALSE)

# print a summary of the model
